{"title_page": "Donna Shalala", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Donna Shalala\n| image        = Donna Shalala, official portrait, 116th Congress.jpg\n| state        = [[Florida]]\n| district     = {{ushr|FL|27|27th}}\n| term_start   = January 3, 2019\n| term_end     = \n| predecessor  = [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]]\n| successor    = \n| office1      = President of the [[Clinton Foundation]]\n| term_start1  = March 6, 2015\n| term_end1    = April 25, 2017\n| predecessor1 = Eric Braverman\n| successor1   = [[Kevin Thurm]]\n| office2      = 5th [[University of Miami|President of the University of Miami]]\n| term_start2  = June 1, 2001\n| term_end2    = August 16, 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Edward T. Foote II]]\n| successor2   = [[Julio Frenk]]\n| order3       = 18th\n| office3      = United States Secretary of Health and Human Services\n| president3   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| term_start3  = January 22, 1993\n| term_end3    = January 20, 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Louis Wade Sullivan]]\n| successor3   = [[Tommy Thompson]]\n| office4      = 5th [[List of presidents and chancellors of the University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|Chancellor of the]]<br>[[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n| term_start4  = January 1, 1988\n| term_end4    = January 22, 1993\n| predecessor4 = [[Bernard Cecil Cohen]]\n| successor4   = [[David Ward (university president)|David Ward]]\n| office5      = 10th [[Hunter College|President of Hunter College]]\n| term_start5  = October 8, 1980\n| term_end5    = January 1, 1988\n| predecessor5 = Jacqueline Grennan Wexler\n| successor5   = [[Paul LeClerc]]\n| office6      = [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|United States Assistant Secretary of Housing and Urban Development for Policy Development and Research]]\n| term_start6  = January 1977\n| term_end6    = October 1980\n| president6   = [[Jimmy Carter]]\n| predecessor6 = \n| successor6   = Emanuel S. Savas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/97th-congress/152|title=PN152 \u2013 Nomination of Emanuel S. Savas for Department of Housing and Urban Development|last=97th United States Congress|authorlink=97th United States Congress|date=April 2, 1981|website=[[United States Congress|Congress.gov]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127025837/https://www.congress.gov/nomination/97th-congress/152|archive-date=November 27, 2018 |access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_name   = Donna Edna Shalala\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1941|2|14}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| education    = [[Western College for Women|Western College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>{{nowrap|[[Syracuse University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n| website      = {{url|shalala.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n\n'''Donna Edna Shalala''' ({{lang-ar|\u062f\u0648\u0646\u0627 \u0625\u062f\u0646\u0627 \u0634\u0644\u0627\u0644\u0627}}; {{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|l|e\u026a|l|\u0259}} {{respell|sh\u0259|LAY|l\u0259}}; born February 14, 1941) is an American politician and academic serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|FL|27}} since 2019. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], she previously served as the 18th [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services]] under President [[Bill Clinton]] from 1993 to 2001.\n\nShalala served as President of the [[University of Miami]], a [[private university]] in [[Coral Gables, Florida]], from 2001 through 2015. Previously she was the President of [[Hunter College]] from 1980 until 1988 and chancellor of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] from 1988 to 1993. Shalala also served as Trustee Professor of Political Science and Health Policy at the [[University of Miami]], and was President of the [[Clinton Foundation]] from 2015 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/voices/events/donna-shalala-former-president-of-the-clinton-foundation/|title=Donna Shalala, former President of the Clinton Foundation|first1=677 Huntington Avenue|last1=Boston|first2=|last2=Ma 02115 +1495\u20111000|date=October 20, 2017 |website=Voices in Leadership}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/03/06/donna-shalala-to-lead-clinton-foundation/ |title=Donna Shalala to Lead Clinton Foundation |author=Amy Chozick |work=The New York Times |date=March 6, 2015 |accessdate=March 7, 2015}}</ref> She was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] in the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Florida|2018 election]], in a district which includes just over half of [[Miami]] as well as many of its eastern suburbs.<ref name=\"Miami Herald Win House\">{{cite news |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article220861260.html|title=Shalala rode anti-Trump sentiment to take a congressional seat away from the GOP|last=Clark|first=Lesley|date=2018-11-06|work=Miami Herald|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nShalala was born in [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]] of [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite Catholic]] [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] descent.<ref>{{cite book |title=Great lives from history: American women series Volume 5 |author=Frank Northen Magill |publisher=Salem Press |date=1995}}</ref> Her father sold real estate<ref name=\"NYTimes in the News\" /> and her mother, one of the first Lebanese-Americans to graduate from [[The Ohio State University]],<ref name=\"Miami Herald Edna Obit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/obituaries/article4249167.html|title=Lawyer Edna Shalala, mother of University of Miami president, dies at 103|last=Cohen|first=Howard|date=December 2, 2014|work=Miami Herald|access-date=2018-10-07}}</ref> was a teacher who worked two jobs and attended law school at night.<ref name=\"NYTimes in the News\" /> <ref name=\"Miami Herald Edna Obit\" /> She has a [[twin]] sister, Diane Fritel.<ref name=\"WaPo Lifetime\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uwbadgers.com/news/2018/7/16/general-lucas-2018-uw-athletic-hall-of-fame-donna-shalala.aspx|title=2018 UW Athletic Hall of Fame: Donna Shalala|last=Lucas|first=Mike|date=July 16, 2018|publisher=University of Wisconsin|access-date=August 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShalala attended West Technical High School where she was the editor of the school newspaper.<ref name=\"WaPo Lifetime\" /> She received a [[bachelor's degree]] in 1962 from [[Western College for Women]].{{efn|In 1976, Western College for Women merged with [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED134105.pdf|title=Mergers in Higher Education |access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2000/6/7/at-helm-of-nations-health-donna/|title=At Helm of Nation's Health Donna Shalala Thrives |work=Harvard Crimson |access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> From 1962 to 1964, she was among the first volunteers to serve in the [[Peace Corps]].<ref name=\"Peace Corps\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/04/15/on-a-health-kick/7bafec23-0fb9-4643-9ef9-6838697bc84f/|title=On a Health Kick |last=Vobejda|first=Barbara|date=April 15, 1993|work=The Washington Post|access-date=August 19, 2018}}</ref> Her placement took her to [[Iran]] where she worked with other volunteers to construct an [[agricultural college]].<ref name=\"Peace Corps\">{{cite web |url=http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2021793.html |title=PeaceCorpsOnline web site |publisher=Peace Corps |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> In 1970, she earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] from the [[Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs]] at [[Syracuse University]] in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>[http://www.education.miami.edu/facultystaff/CVs/125.pdf Curriculum Vitae Donna E. Shalala.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140919204317/http://www.education.miami.edu/facultyStaff/CVs/125.pdf |date=September 19, 2014 }} [[University of Miami]]. Retrieved October 19, 2014.</ref>\n\n== Academic career (1970\u20131992) ==\nShalala began her teaching career as a [[political science]] professor at [[Baruch College]] (part of the [[City University of New York]]), where she also was a member of the [[American Federation of Teachers]] union. In 1972, Shalala became a professor of politics and education at [[Teachers College, Columbia University]], a post she held until 1979.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tc.columbia.edu/articles/2009/october/silhouettes-of-tc-today-cover/|title=Silhouettes of TC Today cover |publisher=Teachers College \u2013 Columbia University|access-date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> In 1975, Shalala became the only woman on the [[Municipal Assistance Corporation]], a group tasked with saving [[New York City]] from a financial crisis.<ref name=\"NYTimes in the News\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/12/us/the-transition-woman-in-the-news-emphasis-on-action-donna-edna-shalala.html|title=THE TRANSITION: Woman in the News; Emphasis On Action: Donna Edna Shalala|last=Chira|first=Susan|date=December 12, 1992|work=The New York Times|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> Concurrently, from 1977 to 1980, she served as the assistant secretary for policy development and research at the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development]] during the [[Jimmy Carter|Carter Administration]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://drexel.edu/now/archive/2016/April/Shalala-2016-Drexel-commencement-speaker/|title=Clinton Foundation President Donna Shalala to Address Graduates at Drexel\u2019s Commencement |publisher=DrexelNow|access-date=May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShalala's first experience with academic administration came on October 8, 1980, when she became the tenth president of [[Hunter College]], serving in this capacity until 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catsimatidis.com/secretary-donna-shalala-speaks-at-the-cats-roundtable-radio-show/|title=Secretary Donna Shalala Speaks at the CATS Roundtable Radio Show |date=February 24, 2016 |publisher=John Catsimatidis Official Site|access-date=May 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShalala next served as [[Chancellor (education)#United States|chancellor]] of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] (1988\u20131993).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chancellor.wisc.edu/past-presidents-and-chancellors/|title=Past presidents and chancellors |publisher=Office of the Chancellor, University of Wisconsin |access-date=May 11, 2016}}</ref> At the time of her chancellorship, the university included 42,000 students, employed 16,500 people, and had an annual budget of $1 billion.<ref name=\"NYTimes in the News\" /> She was the first woman to lead a [[Big Ten Conference]] school, and only the second woman in the country to head a major research university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://womeninwisconsin.org/donna-shalala/|title=Donna Shalala|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUnder Shalala's chancellorship and with her support, the university adopted a broad [[speech code]] subjecting students to disciplinary action for communications that were perceived as [[hate speech]]. That speech code was later found unconstitutional by a federal judge.<ref name=\"wpbio1999\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/govt/admin/shalala.htm |title=Donna Shalala biography |work=The Washington Post |date=December 15, 1999 |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> Also while chancellor, Shalala supported passage of a revised faculty [[speech code]] broadly restricting \"harmful\" speech in both \"noninstructional\" and \"instructional\" settings. The faculty speech code was abolished ten years later, after a number of professors were investigated for alleged or suspected violations.<ref>{{cite news |author=Alan Charles Kors from the July 1999 issue |url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/31068.html |title=\"Cracking the Speech Code,\" '&#39;Reason'&#39;, July 1999 |publisher=Reason |date=March 1, 1999 |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> As Madison chancellor, Shalala, with then athletic director [[Pat Richter]], interviewed and hired football coach [[Barry Alvarez]] who went on to become Wisconsin's all-time leader in football wins, with numerous appearances by Wisconsin at the [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Ed Sherman |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-12-19/sports/9312190321_1_wisconsin-donna-shalala-secretary-shalala |title=She Left Wisconsin With a Rosy Outlook, |accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. Secretary of Health and Human Services (1993\u20132001) ==\n[[File:Shalala portrait.jpg|thumb|left|Shalala during her tenure as the Secretary of Health and Human Services.]]\n[[File:President William J. Clinton Signing the Immunization Proclamation.jpg|thumb|right|Shalala with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]] in 1993]]\nFollowing a year serving as chair of the [[Children's Defense Fund]] (1992\u20131993), Shalala was nominated in 1992 by President-elect Bill Clinton for the position of [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services]].<ref name=\"NYTimes in the News\" /> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' labeled her \"one of the most controversial Clinton Cabinet nominees\".<ref name=\"wpbio1999\" /> Her nomination went before the [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|Senate Finance Committee]] in January 1993.<ref name=\"WaPo Lifetime\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/govt/admin/stories/shalala011493.htm|title=Shalala: A Lifetime Spent in the Center of Storms|last=Vobejda|first=Barbara|date=January 14, 1993|newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> At the start of her tenure, the Department of Health and Human Services employed 125,000 people and had a budget of $539 billion.<ref name=\"NYTimes in the News\" />\n\nShalala served in this role for all eight years of his administration, becoming the nation's longest-serving HHS secretary. In 1996, Shalala was the <!--first woman?-->[[designated survivor]] during Clinton's [[State of the Union]] address.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/state-union-designated-survivor-demystified/story?id=21637341|title=Politicos Gather for State of the Union, but 'Designated Survivor' Will Be in Hiding|date=January 27, 2014|publisher=ABC News|access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe was also known for her fervent anti-drug stance.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}} She was the first [[Lebanese-American]] to serve in a [[Cabinet of the United States|Cabinet]] position.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/acc/university-of-miami/article1956600.html|title=UM president Donna Shalala lauded for handling of NCAA investigation|publisher=Miami Herald |access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== University of Miami presidency (2001\u20132015) ==\n{{POV section|date=April 2020}}\nAfter the end of the Clinton administration in 2001, Shalala became president of the [[University of Miami]] (UM).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.miami.edu/profile/dshalala@miami.edu|title=Donna Shalala|publisher=University of Miami|access-date=2018-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507214032/https://people.miami.edu/profile/dshalala@miami.edu|archive-date=May 7, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> She created a UM fundraising campaign called \"Momentum,\" designed to raise UM's endowment from approximately $750&nbsp;million to $1&nbsp;billion; the goal was later increased to $1.25 billion by the end of 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.miami.edu/um-surpasses-1.6-billion-m2-campaign-goal.html|title=UM Surpasses $1.6 Billion M2 Goal|last=News|first=U. M.|website=University of Miami News and Events|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref> In February 2012, the University of Miami announced Momentum2: The Breakthrough Campaign for the University of Miami, with $906 million already raised at the time of the public launch. On October 26, 2012, UM announced that Momentum2 hit the $1 billion mark, on track to reach the fundraising goal of $1.6 billion in 2016.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nDrawing on her experience after serving as Secretary of Health and Human Services, Shalala taught a course on the United States healthcare system every spring semester.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn January 20, 2012, the Chronicle of Higher Education reported that Shalala had been paid almost a half million dollars in 2010 to serve on the boards of three companies, two of which were run by UM trustees.<ref>Stripling, Jack; Board Conflicts Abound for College Chiefs; Chronicle of Higher Education; January 15, 2012; [https://www.chronicle.com/article/Conflicts-Abound-for-College/130340]</ref> She served on the board of Lennar Corp,, a development company, from 2001-2012. When she left Lennar, the company reported it was to avoid a \"conflict of interest.\" Lennar's CEO, Stuart Miller, had joined the UM Board of Trustees in 2002. Shalala rejoined Lennar in 2017, after she was no longer President of the University.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/donna-shalalas-pine-rockland-sale-angers-environmentalists-10172462|title=Environmentalists Slam Shalala for Selling Endangered Pine Rocklands to Walmart Developer|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=2018-03-15|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the University of Miami sold 88 acres of undeveloped Pine Rocklands, one of the last remnants of the imperiled habitat in Miami Dade County outside of Everglades National Park, to Ram Realty Services, for $22 million. The Miami New Times described this amount as \"a complete steal for the developer in light of the relative worth of nearby property.\" Also in 2013, Ram Realty and Lennar Corp, worked on at least one project together in North Carolina.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWhen Shalala ran for the US Congress in 2018, her candidacy was opposed by local environmentalists for her part in the sale of the UM pine rocklands site.  Cully Waggoner, VP of the Pine Rocklands Commission, stated, \"\"She can't be trusted, and now she is running for Congress. How much more damage can she inflict on Miami?\"  Al Sunshine, a former TV news reporter and member of the Miami Pine Rocklands Coalition, wrote, \"we want to let her know what WE THINK of her actions to sell off the UM South Campus to be bulldozed for more urban sprawl...For years we tried reaching out to her on this issue. For years, she ignored us.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShalala faced some criticism for her response to a nationally publicized [[University of Miami 2006 custodial workers' strike|custodial workers' strike]] at the University of Miami, which lasted from February 28, 2006, until May 1, 2006. Critics called UM's custodial workers among the lowest paid university-based custodians in the nation and alleged they were not earning a [[living wage]]. The strike prompted Shalala to raise wages. Shalala was also criticized for living in luxury while the custodians did not have health insurance.<ref name=\"GOODNOUGH\">{{cite news|title=Anger Rises on Both Sides of Strike at U. of Miami|last=Goodnough |first=Abby |date=April 18, 2006|work=The New York Times|author2=Steven Greenhouse|page=A.18}}</ref> Shalala criticized union organizer's tactics, including a [[sit-in]] that she said prevented students from attending classes.<ref name=\"GOODNOUGH\" />\n\nIn the fall of 2007, Shalala was inducted into UM's [[Iron Arrow Honor Society]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn September 8, 2014, Shalala announced that she would be stepping down at the end of the 2014\u20132015 academic year.<ref>Chang, Daniel, Michael Vasquez and David Smiley, [https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article1991103.html \"University of Miami President Shalala announces she will retire in 2015\"], Miami Herald via Sun Sentinel, September 8, 2014. Retrieved 2018-12.30.</ref>\n\n== Clinton Foundation (2015\u20132017) ==\nIn 2015, Shalala took a leave of absence from her tenured professorship at UM to volunteer for the [[Clinton Foundation]].<ref name=\"Miami Herald UM\">{{cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article146752404.html|title=Former Clinton Foundation head Donna Shalala is back in Miami and at UM|last=Charles|first=Jacqueline|date=2017-04-25|work=Miami Herald |access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> She followed her tenure as president of the University of Miami with being named chief executive officer of the Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donna-shalala-to-lead-clinton-foundation-1425676577 |title=Donna Shalala to Lead Clinton Foundation|last=Nicholas|first=Peter|last2=Reinhard|first2=Beth |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Chelsea Clinton]] helped persuade Shalala to leave the Miami position, move to New York and head the foundation.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie|last2=Chozick |first2=Amy |date=September 29, 2015 |title= Donna Shalala, President of Clinton Foundation, Has Stroke |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/01/us/donna-shalala-president-of-clinton-foundation-has-stroke.html |work=The New York Times |access-date= September 30, 2015}}</ref> Shalala maintained a home in Miami and taught part-time at UM while heading the foundation in New York.<ref name=\"Miami Herald UM\" />\n\nShalala led the Clinton Foundation during the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], in which [[Hillary Clinton]] was a leading candidate and the propriety of the foundation's activity came under scrutiny.<ref name=\"Miami Herald UM\" /> In a September 14, 2016, interview on MSNBC, Shalala admitted that there was \u201cno question\u201d that donors to the Clinton Foundation had been given \u201ccourtesy appointments\u201d in the State Department while Hillary Clinton ran that department.<ref>Mitchel, Andrea; Clinton Foundation preps for change; MSNBC; September 14, 2016; [https://www.msnbc.com/andrea-mitchell-reports/watch/clinton-foundation-preps-for-change-764877379582?v=raila&]</ref> Shalala oversaw the termination of the Clinton Global Initiative during her tenure as CEO,<ref name=\"Miami Herald UM\" /> as well as other reductions in operations intended to avoid conflicts of interest if Clinton won the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/09/15/politics/clinton-foundation-donna-shalala/index.html |title=Clinton Foundation president rebuts Trump's 'pay-for-play' accusations|last=Bradner|first=Eric|date=2016-09-15|publisher=CNN |access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> She resisted calls by ''The Washington Post'' and ''USA Today'' to shut down the foundation entirely, arguing that \"there are human beings around the world who would be affected by these decisions.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-clintonfoundation/chorus-grows-for-clintons-to-shutter-charitable-foundation-idUSKCN10Z20Y|title=Chorus grows for Clintons to shutter charitable foundation|last=Heavey|first=Susan|date=2016-08-24 |publisher=Reuters|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\nShalala left the Clinton Foundation in April 2017 to return to her full-time teaching position at UM; she was replaced by her former HHS deputy [[Kevin Thurm]].<ref name=\"Miami Herald UM\" />\n\n=== 2015 stroke ===\nFollowing a September 2015 Clinton Global Initiative event held at the [[Sheraton New York]], Shalala fell ill. It was subsequently reported by a foundation statement that she had suffered a [[stroke]].<ref name=\"New York Times\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/article37014084.html|title=Former UM president Donna Shalala suffers stroke|publisher=Miami Herald |access-date=April 14, 2016}}</ref> As of early 2018, she claimed to have \"totally recovered.\"<ref name=\"AP fight Trump\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/b9831a35916a40b4bb88906f11eb402f|title=Donna Shalala seeks to fight Trump if elected to Congress |last=Gomez Licon|first=Adriana|date=2018-03-08|agency=Associated Press|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives (2019\u2013present) ==\n\n=== 2018 campaign ===\n{{main|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Florida#District 27}}\n\nIn March 2018, Shalala declared her candidacy in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary for [[Florida's 27th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/former-cabinet-secretary-donna-shalala-to-run-for-congress-in-miami/2018/03/06/a2f6d9ae-215a-11e8-badd-7c9f29a55815_story.html|title=Former Cabinet secretary Donna Shalala to run for Congress in Miami|last1=Scherer|first1=Michael|date=March 6, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article203649559.html|title=Donna Shalala is running for Congress in bid to replace Ros-Lehtinen|last1=Daugherty|first1=Alex|last2=Smiley|first2=David|date=March 5, 2018|work=[[Miami Herald]] |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> The district voted overwhelmingly for Clinton in the 2016 presidential election, but its House seat was held by 30-year incumbent Republican [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]].<ref name=\"AP fight Trump\" />\n\nIn an interview with [[WFOR-TV]], Shalala stated that she supported universal healthcare coverage, but opposed a [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare For All]] [[single-payer healthcare]] system because she believed that individuals who liked their current employment-based healthcare plans should be able to keep them.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://miami.cbslocal.com/video/3823685-web-video-extra-full-interview-with-congressional-candidate-donna-shalala/|title=Web Video Extra: Full Interview With Congressional Candidate Donna Shalala|date=March 8, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Miami]]|access-date=August 17, 2018}}</ref> On August 28, 2018, Shalala won the Democratic five-candidate primary over state Representative [[David Richardson (Florida politician)|David Richardson]]. The outcome of the race was substantially closer than polling predicted, which had her leading consistently by double digits. She won with 31.9 percent of the vote, vs. 27.5% for Richardson.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.local10.com/news/elections/shalala-wins-democratic-primary-for-us-house-florida-district-27|title=Shalala wins Democratic primary for U.S. House Florida...|last=Morejon|first=Andrea Torres, Liane|date=August 28, 2018 |publisher=[[WPLG]]|access-date=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShalala ran against Republican candidate [[Maria Elvira Salazar]], a popular anchorwoman for Miami Telemundo outlet [[WSCV]], in the general election. Shalala's campaign emphasized her experience and sought to tie Salazar to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]], who was unpopular in the district.<ref name=\"Miami Herald Win House\" /> The race proved closer than expected, in part because Shalala does not speak Spanish; the 27th district is over 63 percent Latino. As late as a month before the election, polls showed Shalala either behind or practically tied with Salazar.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/latest-news/article218956830.html|title=Everybody knows her name, but Donna Shalala is finding it difficult to get to Congress|author1=Lesley Clark|publisher=[[McClatchy Washington Bureau]]|date=October 7, 2018}}</ref> However, Shalala won the election at the age of 77, making her the second-oldest freshman Representative in history<ref name=\"Miami Herald Win House\" /> after [[James B. Bowler]] who was elected at the age of 78 in 1953. Her victory returned the seat to the Democrats for the first time since the death of longtime congressman [[Claude Pepper]] in 1989.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nShalala was sworn in as a member of the [[116th United States Congress]] on January 3, 2019. She is the oldest freshman member of the House.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn April 17, 2020, Shalala was appointed by House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] to serve on the [[COVID-19 Congressional Oversight Commission]] to oversee the implementation of the ''[[Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act|CARES Act]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/493469-pelosi-appoints-rep-donna-shalala-to-coronavirus-oversight-panel|title=Pelosi appoints Rep. Donna Shalala to coronavirus oversight panel|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=2020-04-18|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nOn December 18, 2019, Shalala voted to impeach President Donald J. Trump. <ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-impeachment-vote-results-house-2019-12</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and Labor|Committee on Education and Labor]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Rules|Committee on Rules]]'''\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n*'''[[Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus]]'''\n*'''[[Congressional Solar Caucus]]'''\n\n== Other activities ==\n\n=== Board memberships ===\nShalala is currently serving on the Board of Directors of the [[United States Soccer Federation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/about/governance/board-of-directors|title=Board of Directors|website=www.ussoccer.com}}</ref> Shalala served as a member of the board of directors of [[Lennar Corporation]] from 2001\u20132012.<ref name=\"www6.miami.edu\">{{cite web |url=https://ucomm.miami.edu/_assets/apache-error-pages/404.html|title=Error 404: Page Not Found|website=ucomm.miami.edu}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |title=Donna Shalala, Independent Director|publisher=Morningstar|url=http://insiders.morningstar.com/trading/executive-profile.action?t=LEN&PersonId=PS00000D87&flag=Director&region=USA&culture=en-US|accessdate=March 13, 2011}}</ref> She served on the board of directors of [[Gannett Company]] from 2001 to 2011, retiring because of age limits.<ref>{{cite news|last=Clabaugh|first=Jeff |title=Donna Shalala leaves Gannett board|publisher=Business Journal|date=February 23, 2011 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/news/2011/02/23/shalala-leaves-gannett-board.html|accessdate=March 13, 2011}}</ref>\nThe [[Chronicle of Higher Education]] has reported on the [[conflict of interest]] of Shalala sitting on boards of property development companies.<ref>[http://chronicle.com/article/Conflicts-Abound-for-College/130340/ Conflicts Abound for College Chiefs on Corporate Boards] \u2013 The Chronicle of Higher Education</ref>\n\n=== Co-chair of Presidential Commission ===\nOn March 6, 2007, President [[George W. Bush]] named Shalala and [[Bob Dole]] to head a presidential commission called the ''President's Commission On Care for America's Returning Wounded Warriors.'' The commission was formed in response to a growing outcry over the care of wounded outpatient soldiers.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:President Bush Meets with Co-Chairs of the President's Commission on Care for America's Returning Wounded Warriors.jpg|thumb|President Bush Meets with Co-Chairs of the President's Commission on Care for America's Returning Wounded Warriors|right]]\nThe commission included seven other members, ranging from injured war veterans to the wife of a wounded staff sergeant who suffered burns across 70 percent of his body. Demands for corrective action arose after ''[[The Washington Post]]'' exposed living conditions in a decrepit Army-owned building just outside [[Walter Reed Hospital]] and highlighted obstacles and delays in the treatment of soldiers who suffered serious injuries in [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2089603.html |title=PeaceCorpsOnline |publisher=Peace Corps |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> The commission subsequently issued several recommendations for improvement of these facilities.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== Civic activities ===\nIn 1985, Shalala became a founding member of [[EMILY's List]], a [[political action committee]] that seeks to elect pro-choice Democratic women to office.<ref name=national>{{cite news|last1=Vaida|first1=Bara|last2=Skalka|first2=Jennifer|title=Can EMILY's List Get Its Mojo Back?|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/magazine/can-emily-s-list-get-its-mojo-back--20080628|publisher=National Journal |date=June 28, 2008|accessdate=February 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205222842/http://www.nationaljournal.com/magazine/can-emily-s-list-get-its-mojo-back--20080628 |archive-date=February 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Shalala served from 2001\u20132007<ref name=\"www6.miami.edu\"/> on the board of the [[Albert Shanker Institute]], a small, three-member staff organization named for the former head of the [[American Federation of Teachers]]. She is an honorary board member of the [[American Iranian Council]], an organization that seeks to promote closer U.S.&nbsp;relations with [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://American-Iranian.org |title=American Iranian Council web site |publisher=American-iranian.org |accessdate=September 23, 2011}}</ref> She served<ref name=\"www6.miami.edu\"/> on the board of directors for [[Gannett Company]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nShalala serves as a co-leader of the Nutrition and Physical Activity Initiative at the [[Bipartisan Policy Center]].<ref>[http://www.bipartisanpolicy.org/projects/nutrition-and-physical-activity-initiative Nutrition and Physical Activity Initiative] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812123325/http://bipartisanpolicy.org/projects/nutrition-and-physical-activity-initiative |date=August 12, 2011}}, Bipartisan Policy Center</ref> She serves as a distinguished senior fellow in the Economic Studies Program and the Engelberg Center for Health Care Reform at the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/think-tanked/post/donna-shalala-former-hhs-secretary-joins-brookings/2012/04/02/gIQA90u0qS_blog.html|title=Donna Shalala, former HHS secretary, joins Brookings|work=The Washington Post |first=Allen|last=McDuffee|date=April 2, 2012}}</ref> She is also a member of Washington D.C based think tank, The [[Inter-American Dialogue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedialogue.org/experts/donna-shalala/|publisher=Inter-American Dialogue |title=Donna Shalala |access-date=April 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Sebelius greets former HHS Secretary Donna Shalala, former Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, and former HHS Secretary Louis Sullivan prior to a bipartisan health reform implementation meeting in Washington, D.C..jpg|thumb|HHS Secretary [[Kathleen Sebelius]] greets Shalala, former Senate Majority Leader [[Bill Frist]], and former HHS Secretary [[Louis Wade Sullivan|Louis Sullivan]] prior to a bipartisan health reform implementation meeting in Washington, D.C., in 2010.|left]]\nShalala also served as a panelist on the [[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]], a working group of former high-ranking government officials and academic experts that put together a set of recommendations regarding the United States' defense capabilities against biological threats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biodefensestudy.org/panel/secretary-donna-shalala|title=Secretary Donna Shalala |publisher=biodefensestudy.org|access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Honors ===\nOn June 19, 2008, Shalala was awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] by President [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/pagelayout/reference/two_column_table/Presidential_Medal_of_Freedom_Recipients.htm|title=U.S. Senate: Presidential Medal of Freedom Recipients|website=www.senate.gov}}</ref> In 2010 she received the Nelson Mandela Award for Health and Human Rights.<ref>[http://kff.org/other/press-release/donna-e-shalala-honored-with-nelson-mandela-award-for-health-and-human-rights/ Donna E. Shalala Honored With Nelson Mandela Award For Health And Human Rights] Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation</ref> She was inducted into the [[National Women's Hall of Fame]] in [[Seneca Falls, New York]] in 2011.<ref name=\"miami.edu\">[http://www.miami.edu/index.php/about_us/leadership/office_of_the_president/president_donna_e_shalalas_biography/ President Donna E. Shalala\u2019s Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717052840/http://www.miami.edu/index.php/about_us/leadership/office_of_the_president/president_donna_e_shalalas_biography |date=July 17, 2015 }} University of Miami</ref> In 2014, she was recognized by the [[Harry S Truman Library and Museum]] with the Harry S Truman Legacy of Leadership Award.<ref>[http://www.miami.edu/index.php/news/releases/president_shalala_honored_with_truman_award/ President Shalala Honored with Truman Award] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209183626/http://www.miami.edu/index.php/news/releases/president_shalala_honored_with_truman_award/ |date=February 9, 2015 }} University of Miami</ref> In 2019, Shalala was announced as one of the members of the inaugural class of the [[Government Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shalala.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2022 |title=Rep. Shalala Named to Inaugural Class of Government Hall of Fame &#124; U.S. Congresswoman Donna Shalala |publisher=Shalala.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2019-08-16}}</ref>\n\nShalala has been awarded more than 50 [[honorary degree]]s.<ref name=\"www6.miami.edu\"/>\n\nShalala has been elected to the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]; [[National Academy of Education]]; the [[National Academy of Public Administration (United States)|National Academy of Public Administration]]; the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]; the [[American Philosophical Society]]; the [[National Academy of Social Insurance]]; the [[American Academy of Political and Social Science]]; and the [[National Academy of Medicine]].<ref name=\"miami.edu\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of female United States Cabinet Secretaries]]\n*[[List of Arab and Middle-Eastern Americans in the United States Congress]]\n*[[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://shalala.house.gov/ Congresswoman Donna Shalala] official U.S. House website\n*[https://donnashalala.com/ Donna Shalala for Congress]\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=182301|congbio=S001206|fec=H8FL27193|congress=donna-shalala/S001206}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101231013408/http://www.miami.edu/index.php/about_us/leadership/office_of_the_president/president_donna_e_shalalas_biography President Donna E. Shalala Biography], University of Miami.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060522185118/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/051022/22shalala.htm \"America's Best Leaders: Q&A with Donna Shalala, President of the University of Miami], ''U.S. News & World Report'', October 22, 2005.\n*[http://www.makers.com/donna-shalala Donna Shalala] Video produced by [[Makers: Women Who Make America]]\n*[http://library.hunter.cuny.edu/old/sites/default/files/pdf/finding_aids/President%20Donna%20Shala